<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-722-935  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 722 935.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Dec 17 1990 v4 n41 p30(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Returning Congress to be knee deep in IRM issues. (informationresources management)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rivenbark, Leigh.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Congress, when it convenes in 1991, will consider two areasthat affect the careers of federal information resourcesmanagement (IRM) officials.andP;  The Procurement Integrity Act wentinto effect on Dec 1, 1990, but enactment of its much-criticizedpost-employment rules were deferred for six months, leaving timeto modify revolving-door provisions.andP;  The definition of when aprocurement actually begins, critical for the bill's employmentrestrictions, will also be better defined.andP;  The status of the BushAdministration's S 2775 bill, which would replace the ProcurementIntegrity Act and focus on the protection of procurement data,also awaits debate.andP;  The second key issue is the reauthorizationof the Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs (OIRA) in theOffice of Management and Budget.andP;  Key disputes are over how muchof the OIRA's regulatory review process should be made public, andthe division of responsibility for disseminating publicinformation between government and private sectors.andP;  PresidentBush's nomination of Vanderbilt law professor James Blumstein asOIRA chief administrator also sits in limbo.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Procurement Integrity Act of 1990 (Interpretation andconstruction).andO;Topic:     LegislationGovernment RegulationGovernment ContractsUnited States. CongressUnited States. Office of Management and Budget. Office ofInformation and Regulatory AffairsInformation Resources ManagementNational GovernmentRequest for ProposalsGovernment Agency.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>